  "intelligenceGlossary": [
    { "term": "ExComm", "definition": "The Executive Committee. A special group of advisors (including the President's brother, Robert Kennedy) assembled to handle the crisis." },
    { "term": "DEFCON", "definition": "Defense Readiness Condition. A 5-level alert system used by the US Military. DEFCON 5 is normal peace; DEFCON 1 is nuclear war." },
    { "term": "Quarantine", "definition": "A naval blockade. The US used the word 'Quarantine' because a 'Blockade' is technically an act of war." },
    { "term": "MRBM", "definition": "Medium-Range Ballistic Missile. A nuclear missile that can travel about 1,000 miles. The Soviet missiles found in Cuba." },
    { "term": "Sortie", "definition": "A combat mission flown by an individual aircraft." },
    { "term": "MAD", "definition": "Mutually Assured Destruction. The idea that if one side attacks with nukes, the other side will fire back, and both nations will be destroyed." },
    { "term": "SAM", "definition": "Surface-to-Air Missile. A defensive missile fired from the ground to destroy aircraft (like the U-2)." }
  ],
  "epilogue": {
    "staticDebrief": "### MISSION DEBRIEF\n\n**System Offline. Reflection Protocols Active.**\n\n1. **The Fog of War:** In the simulation, you didn't know the Soviet submarines had nuclear weapons. How does 'not knowing' change the decisions a leader makes?\n2. **Ethics of Deterrence:** Was trading the Jupiter missiles in Turkey a sign of weakness or a smart compromise? Why did they keep it secret?\n3. **Civilian Control:** Why is it important that a civilian (The President) is in charge of the military, rather than a General?"
  },
