      "id": "target_2",
      "shortTitle": "The ExComm",
      "longTitle": "Target 2: The Response (Oct 18)",
      "interactionPrompt": "The room is split. General LeMay guarantees an airstrike will destroy the missiles. McNamara argues it will fail and start WW3. You must cast the deciding vote on the initial US response strategy.",
      "options": ["Authorize OPLAN 312 (Airstrike)", "Authorize Quarantine (Blockade)"],
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "label": "The Options",
          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/situationroom-1.jpg",
          "credit": "WHITE HOUSE - AI",
          "content": "### THE CABINET ROOM\n\nThe mood is grim. The Executive Committee (ExComm) has been meeting in secret for 48 hours. The table is a battlefield of ideas. \n\n**The Debate:**\nSecretary of Defense Robert McNamara is pushing for a 'Quarantine'—a naval ring of ships around Cuba to stop *new* missiles from arriving. It is a middle ground. It stops the buildup but does nothing about the missiles already on the island.\n\nPresident Kennedy is nervous. He remembers how easy it is for great powers to stumble into a war they don't want. He asks his advisors: 'If we bomb them, will they bomb us back in Berlin?'"
        },
        "legal": {
          "label": "Hawk View",
          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/lemay.jpg",
          "credit": "USAF / GEN. LEMAY - AI",
          "content": "### PROFILE: GENERAL CURTIS LEMAY\n**Chief of Staff, US Air Force**\n\nLeMay is a 'Hawk'—someone who favors aggressive military force. He thinks the blockade is weak. He told the President: *'This is almost as bad as the appeasement at Munich.'* (Referring to when Europe let Hitler take territory without fighting back).\n\n**The Military Guarantee:**\nLeMay promises that the Air Force can destroy 90% of the missiles in the first attack. \n\n**The Risk:**\nMcNamara asks: 'What about the other 10%?' Even one surviving missile hitting Miami would kill millions. LeMay is willing to gamble American lives on his pilots' skill. He believes war is inevitable."
        },
        "intel": {
          "label": "Dove View",
          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/RFK-Mcnamara-1.jpg",
          "credit": "RFK & MCNAMARA - AI",
          "content": "### PROFILE: ROBERT F. KENNEDY (RFK)\n**Attorney General**\n\nRFK is a 'Dove'—someone who favors diplomacy. He is passing notes to his brother, urging him not to be pushed into a war by the Generals.\n\n**The Moral Argument:**\nRFK argues that a surprise attack by a large nation (USA) on a small one (Cuba) violates American values. He calls the Blockade a 'golden bridge'—a way out. It gives the Soviet leader, Khrushchev, a chance to back down without looking like a coward.\n\n**The Calculation:**\nIf we bomb the Soviet technicians in Cuba, the Soviets *must* fight back. This would likely lead to World War III. The Blockade buys time. The Airstrike buys a war."
        }
      }
